\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/lfunction.critical_strip}{Critical strip}}
\begin{definition*}\label{lfunction.critical_strip}
\uses{lfunction.dirichlet_series,lfunction.euler_product,lfunction.functional_equation,lfunction.motivic_weight,lfunction.normalization}
In the \hyperref[lfunction.normalization]{analytic normalization}, the \hyperref[lfunction.functional_equation]{functional equation} relates $s$ to $1-s$ and the
\textbf{critical strip} is the open strip $\{ s \in {\mathbb C}: 0 < \Re(s) < 1 \}$.

In the arithmetic normalization, the functional equation relates $s$ to $1 + w - s$,
where $w$ is the \hyperref[lfunction.motivic_weight]{motivic weight} of the L-function,
and the
\textbf{critical strip} is the open strip $\{ s \in {\mathbb C}: w/2 < \Re(s) < w/2 + 1 \}$.

In either normalization, the \hyperref[lfunction.dirichlet_series]{Dirichlet series} and \hyperref[lfunction.euler_product]{Euler product} converge
absolutely to the right of the critical strip, and so the L-function
does not vanish there.  Therefore all nontrivial zeros
of the L-function lie in (the closure of) the critical strip.
\end{definition*}


